{"id":"2303.08412","submitter":"Jimyeong Kim","authors":"Woocheol Choi and Jimyeong Kim","title":"On the convergence analysis of the decentralized projected gradient\n  descent","comments":"27 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC cs.SY eess.SY","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In this work, we are concerned with the decentralized optimization problem:\n\\begin{equation*} \\min_{x \\in \\Omega}~f(x) = \\frac{1}{n} \\sum_{i=1}^n f_i (x),\n\\end{equation*} where $\\Omega \\subset \\mathbb{R}^d$ is a convex domain and each\n$f_i : \\Omega \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}$ is a local cost only known to agent $i$.\nA fundamental algorithm is the decentralized projected gradient method (DPG)\ngiven by \\begin{equation*}\n  x_i(t+1)=\\mathcal{P}_\\Omega\\Big[\\sum^n_{j=1}w_{ij} x_j(t) -\\alpha(t)\\nabla\nf_i(x_i(t))\\Big] \\end{equation*} where $\\mathcal{P}_{\\Omega}$ is the projection\noperator to $\\Omega$ and $ \\{w_{ij}\\}_{1\\leq i,j \\leq n}$ are communication\nweight among the agents. While this method has been widely used in the\nliteratures, its sharp convergence property has not been established well so\nfar, except for the special case $\\Omega = \\mathbb{R}^n$. This work establishes\nnew convergence estimates of DPG when the aggregate cost $f$ is strongly convex\nand each function $f_i$ is smooth. If the stepsize is given by constant $\\alpha\n(t) \\equiv\\alpha >0$ and suitably small, we prove that each $x_i (t)$ converges\nto an $O(\\sqrt{\\alpha})$-neighborhood of the optimal point. In addition, we\ntake a one-dimensional example $f_i$ and prove that the point $x_i (t)$\nconverges to an $O(\\alpha)$-neighborhood of the optimal point. Also, we obtain\nconvergence estimates for decreasing stepsizes. Numerical experiments are also\nprovided to support the convergence results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 15 Mar 2023 07:27:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-16"}
{"id":"2303.08413","submitter":"Grigore Calugareanu","authors":"Grigore Calugareanu, Horia F. Pop and Adrian Vasiu","title":"On matrix invertible completions over commutative rings","comments":"45 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AC math.RA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study arithmetics of all commutative rings with identity via completions\nof square matrices, stable range considerations, and units and projective\nmodules interpretations. At the core of this work is the class C2 (resp. SC2)\nof commutative rings R with the property that a 2x2 matrix with entries in R\ncan be completed to an invertible 3x3 matrix (resp. to an invertible 3x3 matrix\nwhose (3,3) entry is 0) iff its entries generate R. These two classes of rings\ncontain all semilocal rings, are global in nature, and impact many other\nclasses of rings. For instance, we present several necessary and sufficient\nconditions (criteria) for a Hermitian ring to belong to the C2 (or SC2) class,\none of these being an elementary divisor ring. Implicitly, we reobtain (often\nrefine) known criteria and obtain new criteria for a Hermite ring to be an\nelementary divisor ring. Similarly, a noetherian domain of dimension 1 belongs\nto the C2 (or SC2) class iff it is a principal ideal domain. We use these\ncriteria to show that: (i) each Bezout ring R that is either a J(2,1) domain or\nis an (SU)2 ring (as introduced by Lorenzini) with the property that for each\nnonzero a of R there exists no non-trivial self-dual projective R/Ra-module of\nrank 1 generated by 2 elements (e.g., with the property that all its elements\nare squares), is an elementary divisor domain, thus solving or partially\nsolving problems raised by Lorenzini, and (ii) to obtain new proofs of\nMcGovern's theorem that each Hermite ring that has almost stable range 1 is an\nelementary divisor ring. We show that a ring R belongs to the SC2 (or C2) class\niff the ring R[[x]] belongs to it. We also provide examples of regular finitely\ngenerated Z-algebras, such as polynomials in at least one indeterminate over Z,\nwhich do not belong to the C2 class. Many other classes of rings are introduced\nand studied.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 15 Mar 2023 07:28:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-16"}
